Thank you for your pull request and welcome to our community. We require contributors to sign our Contributor License Agreement, and we don't seem to have you on file. In order for us to review and merge your code, please sign up at https://code.facebook.com/cla - and if you have received this in error or have any questions, please drop us a line at cla@fb.com. Thanks!

**If you are contributing on behalf of someone else (eg your employer)**: the individual CLA is not sufficient - use https://developers.facebook.com/opensource/cla?type=company instead. Contact cla@fb.com if you have any questions.

I'm currently enrolled in a course on software reliability, and I'm interested in using Infer to explore [static memory leaks in Android apps](http://blog.nimbledroid.com/2016/09/06/stop-memory-leaks.html). I've been digging through the repository and reading the docs to try to understand how to best build new checking capabilities. Are there any particularly good commits or PRs that demonstrate how to properly add a new feature to Infer?

Thanks,
Jacob

Hi Jacob,
  Infer already supports detecting some of these bug types (e.g., [`Context`](http://fbinfer.com/docs/infer-bug-types.html#CONTEXT_LEAK) leaks). Extending the detection to handle other cases like `View` leaks or leaks via `SensorManager` would should be pretty straightforward.

The code for reporting `Context` leaks lives [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/interproc.ml#L652), and the tests are [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/tests/codetoanalyze/java/infer/ContextLeaks.java) (runnable with `make test`). I would probably start off by adding the examples from the blog post to see how many of them Infer can already find, and then refine the checker from there.

If you'd rather start from scratch, here's some [docs](http://fbinfer.com/docs/absint-framework.html) on building brand-new checkers on top of the Infer infrastructure.

Hope this helps and let me know if you have any questions!
This is great, thanks @sblackshear!

@mohammedsafiq linters operate on the AST produced by a front-end -- currently there's only support for the clang front-end, so no Java.

Hi, 

I read the documentation that @SuppressWarnings will have no support from v0.10.0. 

Now i have installed v0.10.0 and in my project i have used @SuppressWarnings("infer") in 24 places. I thought after installing v0.10.0 it it will throw 24 errors to replace @SuppressWarnings with @SuppressLint. 

But it is not throwing. So does it mean like @SuppressWarnings will work in v0.10.0??

Any help is appreciated.!!

Hi @mohammedsafiq,

Other tools use `@SuppressWarnings` annotations, so they won't make infer crash but infer will ignore them. In particular, infer may report on methods annotated with `@SuppressWarnings("infer")`.
No. Its not reporting the methods annotated with @SuppressWarnings("infer")
And it is throwing few new NULL_DEREFERENCE issues which is not thrown in previous versions.
If you introduce an obvious bug in one of the methods annotated with `@SuppressWarnings`, does infer report it? Maybe it simply doesn't find any issues anymore on these methods as they are.
Yes I have introduced obvious bug with @SuppressWarnings just to test. Its not reporting. Have you given any backward compatibility?
Can you paste the command you are using and the result of `infer --version`? Thanks!

Regarding the magic number for the license, that's the hash of the license text for the current Android SDK License. Normally user agrees in GUI in Android Studio, or via `sdkmanager` CLI, then `licenses/android-sdk-license` is populated with that hash. In this script it's being done automatically, replacing functionality of `/opt/sdk-tools/android-accept-licenses.sh` in the current image. See https://developer.android.com/studio/intro/update.html#download-with-gradle.

This is actually shaky ground because the user never explicitly agrees to the Android license (the current Dockerfile has this problem too, the license is automatically agreed to without user intervention). So you may want to remove this functionality of agreeing to the license automatically?

One other option (I'm checking now) is installing the Android dependencies from the Ubuntu package repo instead for purposes of having a working sample in the image, it might avoid the licensing problem.
Ubuntu repo versions don't match the versions used in the sample. Could alter the sample to match, but I think having the dependencies continue to auto-download will be less of a headache?

What problems? I don't think it will work incrementally if you first compiled with Apple's clang.

> what if i just replaced infer's version of clang with a symlink to xcode's?

Infer needs a specific version of clang to run which is why it's shipped with infer. This is because it attaches a plugin to clang to read its AST, and this requires to be used with the same version of clang than the version that the plugin was compiled for.
Closing optimistically in case `GCC_PRECOMPILE_PREFIX_HEADER=NO` fixed it for you. Please reopen if not.

In general, in order to to analyze code with infer, you need working compilation command and most of the time we can't tell our users what the right command is.

With your example, let's say you want to analyze `../driver/mmc/core/core.c`:
you probably can't run `infer -- clang -c ../driver/mmc/core/core.c`, as it will miss header search paths. Instead, you need to find Makefile target that builds that file. 

As for analyzing linux kernel - normally kernel compiles only with gcc. Infer uses clang compiler and linux kernel probably won't compile with clang without changing linux source code. It's outside of scope of our project to make linux compile with clang.

Complex makefile projects may require more work to work with `infer`, but we can help with that if we have compilation that works without `infer`. See `libreoffice` as an example:
https://github.com/facebook/infer/issues/545

It can happen that infer fails to analyse a function for some reason. Possible reasons include infer getting confused when trying to understand the code, or the function taking too long to analyse.

When infer reports, calls to skipped functions are simply jumped over, which can leave people wondering why infer won't go inside the function. Including some information why infer skips a function inside such traces would be useful for both users and developers of Infer.

See https://github.com/facebook/infer/issues/572#issuecomment-277070348 for an example of what skipping a function currently looks like. Instead, something like this would be better:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

Relevant files are [paths.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/fb14d31bb71c480e548cfa2bb22a3c2117e698b4/infer/src/backend/paths.ml#L101), and [symExec.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/fb14d31bb71c480e548cfa2bb22a3c2117e698b4/infer/src/backend/symExec.ml#L1058).

This will help understand for instance which condition is being evaluated when infer prints `Condition is true/false`. An example from #572:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

The goal would be for infer to include a different message in the trace, so that `inferTraceBugs` would print this instead:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

The code printing this message is [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/fb14d31bb71c480e548cfa2bb22a3c2117e698b4/infer/src/backend/paths.ml#L455-L456).

See #572 for more details.

Can this issue be extended to also cover an entire `if` condition. To be specific, we currently output `Taking true branch` or `Taking false branch`, but we should ideally print the expression as well.
Referring to [this part of code](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/fb14d31bb71c480e548cfa2bb22a3c2117e698b4/infer/src/backend/paths.ml#L447-L448).
@xennygrimmato yes, that makes sense.

Hi @mohammedsafiq, Eradicate works pretty much like a type checker, where a value annotated @Nullable is considered as always being potentially null, so local checks for null are required.
In particular, Eradicate does not try to understand the flow of values in a method call, such as `notEmpty(name)`. Another way to look at this: it only considers information at method boundaries, so it will give the same result for any implementation of `notEmpty`, including the one which always returns `true`.
Closing for now. Feel free to reopen if there are further questions.

How does Infer partition files for analysis in multicore mode (and how does this relate to cluster makefiles)?

The partition is that each file is one cluster. The makefiles run the clusters in parallel.

Clusters (and Makefiles) exist mainly because of historical reasons: it used to be the case that infer partitioned procedures according to a call graph that it was trying to compute before the analysis. Now we rely on an on-demand analysis of procedures: if the analysis of a procedure `foo` requires the spec of a procedure `goo` (because `foo` calls `goo`, for instance) and `goo` has not been analysed yet (it has no spec), then it schedules the analysis of `goo`.

One additional issue that I just became aware of: annotations on method parameters/return values actually live in the constant pool, not in the method signature. For already-compiled classes (and anything else in the classpath), we parse the method signature and add it to the type environment, but we don't look at the implementation of the method or its constant pool. This is why you're seeing the weird behavior on your example.

The resource predicate information is used to detect and report resource/memory leaks.

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

What I expected was that closing a file resource would trigger `| (Rrelease, Rfile) => "CLOSED"`.

 > So far, I haven't succeeded in building libreoffice because I got a source tarball from master on the GitHub mirror, which doesn't include sources.ver which is required to build.

That's strange, I pulled the sources from gerrit instance and it just worked.

> So the problem is that configure phase must be aware of infer analyzer for makefile integration to work?

In this case, yes.

The way infer is integrated with `make` is a simple `PATH` trick that replaces gcc/clang/... with our wrappers that run infer instead. `PATH` has no power when the path to the compiler is used instead of just its name (eg, `/usr/bin/clang` will not lookup `PATH`, so will bypass infer).

Some build systems such as `cmake` and LibreOffice's custom build system defeat this simple mechanism, and `PATH` has to be set earlier, at configuration time, so that the path to the compiler is set to infer: `infer -a compile -- ./configure` or `infer -a compile -- cmake` will do this.

Found a workaround for `configure` phase: compiled `clang` from trunk, and used it with `libstdc++` as usual. After configure step, I replaced in config_host.mk `CC`, `CXX` and `COMPATH` with the right value for my `infer` installation. Now after calling `infer --cxx -- make` I am getting this report: [1], mostly complaining about `unique_ptr` redefinition. 

*  [1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/593905/

Those errors are because we have our own simplified headers for `std::unique_ptr` so that analyzer understands it. Unfortunately, in your case those headers conflict with standard ones and we didn't catch it (see below for more info). If you can compile infer from source, you can work around this problem by changing one line in `ClangCommand.re`: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/clang/ClangCommand.re#L32
simply change it to `let infer_cxx_models = false`. It will make analysis worse (no null dereference in `shared_ptr`, `unique_ptr`, no EMPTY_VECTOR_ACCESS from `vector`), but you should be able to run infer.

The reason why you are hitting this problem is because mechanism we model `unique_ptr` is fragile. We 'replace' normal headers with ours by providing another `bits/unique_ptr.h` header which normally works. Unfortunately, there is weird implementation in one of stdlibc++ headers (`bits/locale_conv.h`) which includes `bits/unique_ptr.h` via `#include "unique_ptr.h"` and we can't detect that.
I have plans to change this mechanism, but I suspect it will take a while to complete.

If we get more reports like this, I'll try to think of better workaround for the problem. The most trivial one for you would be to copy-paste contents of `/path/to/stdc++/include/bits/locale_conv.h` to `infer/models/cpp/include/bits/locale_conv.h` and then replace faulty `#include "unique_ptr.h"` with `#include <bits/unique_ptr.h>` (then you could revert previous workaround I suggested)

The next problem I'm running into, in LO we create files, like UNO compiler and then generate classes from type library description. Now these files are instrumented too, and the execution of these targets in make is now failing with:

The problem with infer's current mechanism is that we replace std headers with different ones which are not equivalent (`shared_ptr` is not refcounted for example) and hence we explicitly disallow to run binaries that were created with our headers. In your case, it looks like that you
1. create a tool X to do something with code
2. run X to produce something
3. use results of (2) as source for compilation (?)

To fix this, I see two options:
Option one:
I assume you have target in `make` that does only (3) and there is target that does (1) and (2)
<S_CODE_TOKEN>

Option two:
Similar to what your tried to achieve in last comment - you can try to exclude directories that are responsible for tools created in (1). Create `.inferconfig` file in project root directory (which by default is the directory you run infer from) and specify parameter called `skip-clang-analysis-in-path` with paths relative to project root directory (it can be path to directory, not separate files).

Both of those options should hit [the same code path in infer](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/clang/Capture.re#L161) and simply compile tool X.

Hi Michael,
  We don't currently have any special support for JUnit annotations like `@Test`, but we could add support if there is a need.

In general, I'm skeptical of the utility of statically analyzing small pieces of test code like your example (since one can always just run the code and let JUnit check if the right thing happens). But I'm intrigued by the possibility of using JUnit assertions to specify statically checkable contracts in non-test code. Let me me know if you are interested in that use case/have examples and we can try to throw some support together.

Thanks a lot for the feedback!

For us, this has come up as part of various larger code bases. (I agree that static analysis of small snippets is of limited use.) My example was just intended so as to have a reproducible test scenario. Arguably we could work on ways to exclude tests from the analysis altogether.

For specifications, I am wondering whether JUnit is most suitable; wouldn't JML possibly be a better approach?

Another issue that is independent of annotations is that infer does consider whether there is an enclosing handler for RuntimeExceptions.  In the larger code bases, do you rely on catching RuntimeExceptions and want infer to not report raising them in cases where they will be caught?  Such a change might be quite involved.

A tad unrelated direction is to use infer's blacklisting options to avoid analysing or reporting on these files, unless tests and regular source codes are mixed together.

For instance: `--infer-blacklist-files-containing "@Test("` or `--infer-blacklist-files-containing "import org.junit.Test;"`. These options (like all options) can also go into a .inferconfig file.

Hi, 
Most of us don't use a debugger to debug Infer. We just print elements, most of the IR elements have print functions, so we use those. To debug the symbolic execution in particular, we use html files that have printed most of the execution. You get those files with the option --debug, there is an html file for each source file in the folder infer-out/captured. Also, when you print things, if you use Logging.out, the output is only available in debug mode, and in infer-out/log/....

The whitelist is so that infer doesn't skip analyzing a file that would otherwise be blacklisted. `--changed-files-index` tells infer where to start the analysis from and makes sure all the files in the index are re-analyzed by infer. Without `--changed-files-index` infer will analyze all the files that were captured (or, if `--reactive` was passed, all the files that infer finds have changed since the last run). The blacklist/whitelist options is another mechanism on top of that; for instance, if a file in the index is blacklisted, it will still not be analyzed.

> - Can multiple parallel processes analyze the same procedure even though it is not recursive?
> - Is there any mechanism to protect the race condition?

I should have also mentioned this before, but yes, parallel processes can analyze the same procedure simultaneously.  There are mechanisms to protect against reading partially written files, for when one process reads the specs of a procedure while another is writing them, etc.  But there is intentionally nothing blocking multiple parallel processes from analyzing any individual procedure simultaneously.  The intended usage is to write an analysis which produces a spec for each procedure such that if multiple processes analyze the procedure in parallel, they will obtain the same spec, so it does not matter which process wins the race to write the spec.  It is important and can be nontrivial to design the analysis so that the computed specs are always the same.  Any use of global or file system state must be done with care, and other sources of non-determinism need to be minimized or eliminated.

Yes, by default the analysis runs in parallel, unless it fails to determine the number of processors your machine has.  You can specify explicitly with `-j N`.

> Is it guaranteed that one procedure is analyzed only once?

No.  If procedures are recursive, they may be analyzed a few times.  Each procedure should have only a single spec written to disk, however.

Also, multiple parallel processes may analyze the same procedure multiple times and race to write the spec to disk.

We read more Infer code and our issue became more clear. I remind you about our situation.

1. A callee(`foo`) and a caller(`main`) are in different files.
2. A bug is in the callee.
3. When analyzing the callee, we are not sure that the code is buggy. Thus, after analyzing the callee, we do not report the bug yet.
4. After analyzing the caller, we are sure there is a bug in the callee. So we report it then.

The bug report code is as follows. Since we use the `caller_name` as the seccond argument, the bug info is added to caller(`main`)'s summary.
<S_CODE_TOKEN>

 A problem is when printing it to `report.json`.  `InferPrint.IssueJson.pp_issues_of_error_log` constructs a record, `bug`, for printing, but the location is strange; the line/column number from `foo`'s file, but the file name from `main`'s.
<S_CODE_TOKEN>

This causes an incorrect report. Even though, the bug is in `foo`, the file of `main` is printed.
The line number `2` is about the file of `foo`, not of `main`.
<S_CODE_TOKEN>

As of now, we are using `loc.Location.file` instead of `file` when constructing the `bug` record, but not sure it is a correct way. Can you give us some advice?

I would recommend reporting an interprocedural trace starting at `main` and ending in `foo`. There's a general mechanism for creating and displaying such traces. To check out the visualization, you can run Infer (the bi-abduction analyzer) on a file with an interprocedural trace, then run `inferTraceBugs` (as described [here](http://fbinfer.com/docs/infer-workflow.html)).

To get your own nifty traces that can be visualized by `inferTraceBugs`, you'll need to create an [`Errlog.loc_trace`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/IR/Errlog.ml#L27). You can then pass this trace to the `ltr` parameter `Reporting.log_error` ([example](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/quandary/TaintAnalysis.ml#L182)).

With the information you have in your current domain, I *think* you'll only be able to give the starting point and ending point of the trace (i.e., `main` and `foo` but not `callsFoo` if the call graph is `main` -> `callsFoo` -> `foo`), but that's still a great start! In the long run, it might be useful to change the domain so you can report the entire path.

That's the issue. Your system doesn't supply the version of glibc++ needed by the precompiled plugin that we provide. You can either install that version on your system (probably by upgrading your version of gcc) or recompile clang and its plugin yourself by following the instructions to install infer from source in INSTALL.md.

What system are you using?

Note that none of our releases include a binary version of the analyzer for reasons beyond our control. We do include a precompiled clang and clang plugins, but that's exactly what's causing your issue here because they are compiled with a version of glibc++ incompatible with your system.

Why the archive for 0.9.0 include `infer/bin/infer` and this one is not including it anymore ?
https://github.com/facebook/infer/releases/download/v0.9.0/infer-linux64-v0.9.0.tar.xz

`infer/bin/infer` used to be a Python script that called the analyzer, the plugin, etc. While the toplevel `infer` executable could be shipped as-is, everything else still needed to be compiled for `infer` to work. So the situation hasn't changed since 0.9.0, except for the fact that the toplevel `infer` command is now also written in OCaml and so needs compiling.

Regarding your issue, I think it would help if we provided statically linked binaries for clang and the clang plugins instead of relying on some of the host system's libraries.
Do you consider to create a .deb package with it in the future ?

Statically linking the C(++) runtime is a bad idea.  It is also not supported by the underlying toolchain.  So for the statically link glibc aspect of this issue, I would label it "wont fix".

Please open a separate issue about alternate packaging and distribution, or add to e.g. #470 .

For the particular build failure in the original issue, I'm closing this optimistically, but please reopen if  building the current version wholly from source to resolve library version issues does not work.

I think that the triple you want is what can/will inferred for the on-paper version of the bi-abduction algorithm, but the Infer implementation chooses to report a warning in this case for pragmatic reasons (assuming that all branches are reachable in some context lets us report more bugs without causing too many false positives).

(Copying @cristianoc and @ddino since they have better knowledge about how the theory and practice diverge here.)

Notice that Infer works bottom-up, so if `g` calls `f` then Infer's decision on whether reporting on `f` will not be affected by how `g` calls it.
For example, If `f` contains `if (a) {Object o = null; o.toString();}` then the error is reported in `f` no matter how it's called.
If `f` contains instead `if (a) {o.toString();}` then nothing is reported in `f` but will be reported in `g` if it calls `f` the wrong way (with `a=true` and `o=null`).
Being bottom-up, it might be difficult to model the typical top-down reachability question, as if the error is reported half way through the chain of calls, it won't be reported in calls higher up the call stack.
One attempt could be to put a dereference in the code that you wish to know if reachable, as in `foo(Object r,...) { ...r.toString;...}`
Then pass r through each call, untouched, and only call it with `null` from `main`, or from the roots of the program where one would like to know if it's reachable.
Another proviso is that the analysis might fail for a number of reasons (errors found, limits to the number of operations, etc), so it might not explore all the paths, and fail to report reachability.

Hey @boyue !
In this line:
`IMByteSendStream sendStream = new IMByteSendStream(new ByteArrayOutputStream());`
the `ByteArrayOutputStream()` resource has been passed to `IMByteSendStream` and has not been closed. I think that is the reason for the leak.
Can you try closing both resources in the `finally` block?
Can you tell us what the error message was? Could it be that there was a potential exception in the code? Resource leaks sometimes happen when close() is not done on an exception path.

Also, this link explains some common issues and how to resolve them.
   http://fbinfer.com/docs/infer-bug-types.html#RESOURCE_LEAK

when i use infer to check a ios project which size is 178MB , infer analyse the problem takes 30Gb memory  ,so it is interrupted  with exit code (  macbook pro with 8G rom ),is there anybody who can tell me how to analyse such big project?

We are currently working to reduce memory consumption.  Currently there is not much in the way of configuration options to reduce memory consumption.  One possible option is to set `skip-clang-analysis-in-path` in .inferconfig or on the command line to avoid analyzing particularly problematic code.  Identifying this code is somewhat roundabout, as you need to, while infer is running, observe which InferAnalyze process(es) consume the most memory, look at the command line to see which 'cluster' it is analyzing (clNNN for some number NNN), and then find that cluster in the generated Makefile (infer-out/multicore/Makefile), and look at the comment in that Makefile that indicates which source file(s) the cluster corresponds to.

The `icfg.dot` files mentioned in the debug mode documentation might be more along the lines of what you are looking for. You can view the CFG in these files using `dotty` or any other tool that understands the graphviz format. I think that there might be some confusion here about what information `icfg.dot` is presenting.  The `icfg.dot` files contain the static control-flow graph, which is determined by the source code and control-flow paths that might be impossible are not removed.

From the comments, with the mention of e.g. "which variable is symbolic", it seems that @zzy assumes that infer operates in a way similar to King-style symbolic execution.  I don't think that trying to understand what infer does in these terms is useful, since what it actually does is very different.  A better starting point is probably http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2049697.2049700.

Hello infer dev-team,

compiling/installing infer seems to be a common problem.

Personal experience (on Mac):
I have had trouble installing infer 0.8.1 in the beginning and managed to get it compiled/installed after half a day.
I had problems installing infer 0.9.1? and gave up.

There are also some issues here on github regarding installation.

Since tools/Xcode/command line utilities/libraries/OS and so on constantly change, it is a lot of effort to maintain a working installation script.

Wouldn't it make the lives of ordinary developers like me easier, if there was a binary distribution of infer? Wouldn't it be hard enough for all the great developers, who work on infer, to figure out the right set of libraries/compilers/environemnt? Couldn't their achievements of getting infer compiled on their machines be harnessed and transferred in binary self-contained form to other developers?

I am not such a good developer to be aware of all the consequences and the pros of source distribution (except for allowing further development) over binary distribution. I might be overlooking something. But I wonder, why "normal" consumer facing applications like the ones on the App Stores are distributed in binary form and usually survive many more OS updates and library changes on the system (due to static linking?), yet source distribution is so popular.

Thank you for writing this great tool and making it available publicly!
Kind regards
Nikolas

globals are very tricky to get right and we prefer to just treat them as "safe" to avoid false positives. I'd say it has low priority for us right now.

Could you share your model code as well? I understand you need to model `PQfinish` and `PQconnectdb` to get any useful reports

Sure, but wouldn't it be possible to model a static global as an argument which is passed to every function that is defined within a module?

[Here is my model.](https://bitbucket.org/sumerman/pgtask/src/1308927e613c5663775262d5750088bceaf8fd9c/infer_model/libpq.c?at=infer&fileviewer=file-view-default) It has caught [this](https://bitbucket.org/sumerman/pgtask/commits/1308927e613c5663775262d5750088bceaf8fd9c?at=infer) but not the obvious one.

Regarding globals - there are many options to treat global variables better, your suggestion is one of them. The problem is that tracking many variables in each function can cause performance issues and/or confuse analyzer.

I reproduced your problem and unfortunately it's known limitation of C analysis - infer doesn't treat structs in C very well. In particular, pass-by-value and return-by-value confuse our analyzer right now. In your code, `exit_nicely` confuses infer and then when you call it in line 66, analyzer gives up with `PRECONDITION_NOT_MET` error. Minimized example looks like this:
https://gist.github.com/akotulski/7e73ef3ef8b0f9d9d1155dc1843b4dd3

Structs in C++ have much better support and the same example works for me in C++ mode, but I understand it may not be an option to you. I tested example above in C++ mode (`infer --cxx -- clang -x c++ -c test.c`) and it reported resource leak.

There is open task to address those problems with structs in C, but no one is actively working on it right now.

UPDATE: to illustrate the problem, changing `exit_nicely` to take `state*` instead of `state` triggers `RESOURCE_LEAK` reports as well.

Seems like the skip translation matchers only match with source file contents or method names

https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/7e59032a427769e8003d8bf3c34d207b81f47d3d/infer/src/backend/inferconfig.ml#L196

This makes it very hard to exclude auto generated source files from codegen for skipping translation in Infer.

Seems like the a new `FilePatternMatcher` can be supported for this.

Once that is available, it would be nice to auto exclude generated source folders in build systems like buck automatically
What kind of information could be used to distinguish those generated files ?

The best information to distinguish these files is the directory where they come from. All generated sources typically have an ancestor dir that contains them.

Looking at the generated source itself is not reliable because all annotation processors/gradle plugins etc do not produce similar generated code or annotate them the same way

In https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/e1f19192c07caf2fa0a2ea4fd6692e3de9cddbcd/infer/lib/python/infer.py#L34

the commands to look for are hardcoded to invoke the correct modules. This prevents users the flexibility to wrap such commands in their own.

For example, we wrap all buck invocations in a `buckw` script to perform some steps before the actual buck run and invoke it like `./buckw build target`, very similar to `./gradlew task`

Can there be a configuration option in inferconfig that can specify aliases to different commands?

Right now there is no such option - you may try adding `buckw` to the list in line you provided, but it's not guaranteed to out of the box for `buck` (we may have hardcoded `buck` in our buck integration).

Another short term solution is to make `which buck` point to your script, but I can imagine it may not be an option for you.

As for adding an option, we could add it in following form (modulo naming):

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

Our filtering heuristics tend to rank reports where an explicit flow of null to a dereference site is observed as high-confidence, and reports where a variable is compared to `null` and then dereferenced (such as the example here) as low-confidence.

We ran the [SATE V Ockham Sound Analysis Criteria](https://samate.nist.gov/SATE5OckhamCriteria.html) to better understand sound analyzers. Would anyone be interested in running Infer for another Ockham? Basically that consists of running an analyzer on a substantial set of code that we select and sending us the results. We'd also appreciate answering questions about details of the results that arise.

-paul-
paul.black@nist.gov

@brotherpaul143 Thanks for your interest in Infer. Perhaps there is some oversight, but as far as we understand Infer does not satisfy the SATE criteria. Infer produces two basic forms of output: 1) specifications of procedures / functions / methods, and 2) issue reports for property violations. Only the inferred specifications are claimed to be sound (subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions). Here the notion of sound is that from the logical tradition. In particular, if infer produces {P} f(x) {Q}, then soundness means that execution of f from any state satisfying P does not crash and unless it diverges, the state after f returns satisfies Q. The reports of property violations are produced primarily from failed proofs of such specifications. There is no definition of correctness for these reports, let alone a claim of soundness for them.

The Ockham criteria was established to highlight the strength of analyzers using rigorous inference, in contrast to those that use heuristics. It does not require that all results be absolutely correct (halting problem, after all). Rather, are there some results that are correct? Since Infer results of {P} f(x) {Q} are always correct, given the qualifications you mention, I believe Infer would be consonant with the goals of Ockham.

@brotherpaul143 it seems that Infer and SATE use two opposite definitions of correct/sound. From your website:

"1. The tool is claimed to be sound."

and

"Sound means every finding is correct. The tool need not produce a finding for every site; that is completeness."

This is simply not the case for Infer: reports made by Infer may not correspond to an actual weakness in the code.

Note that Infer is sound in the logical sense, which seems to correspond to your notion of "completeness": if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs (as @jberdine said, "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions"). Infer reports a bug when it fails to prove that a procedure has no bugs (and when Infer's internal heuristics suggest that it may correspond to a real issue, otherwise Infer would be too noisy), not when it can prove that a procedure definitely has a bug.

I agree with you, @jvillard   Please note that Ockham uses the term "finding". The use of "finding" allows an additional level of interpretation. As you point out, "if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs". The _lack_ of a report is a finding for Ockham's purposes. That is, users can absolutely depend on the fact that no bug reportfrom Infer  means that the procedure is bug-free "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions", as @jberdine said.

Infer is welcome to participate in Ockham.

It is unclear how Infer's "findings" could be evaluated or validated.  For example, suppose that for a function `f` Infer computes a specification `{P} f(x) {Q}`.  If Infer is wrong, how can this be demonstrated?  It seems that it would finding a state that satisfies `P` from which executing `f(x)`, subject to Infer's idealistic and optimistic assumptions, either crashes or returns in a state that does not satisfy `Q`.  No mechanized way of doing this is known.  Do you have something else in mind?

@jberdine asks, "Do you have something else in mind?" Yes. There are lots of steps and checks and details and caveats and conditions, but the basic outline is as follows. We choose a test suite with known bugs. If Infer fails to report a bug, then it doesn't satisfy the SATE VI Ockham Criteria. 

I appreciate @jberdine and @jvillard responding to my inquiry. I'm a little surprised with what I perceive as the reluctant attitude. I should think the community would be excited to demonstrate the strengths of Infer. Thank you for your time and patience with me.

@brotherpaul143, Thanks for bringing this up, and I don't mean to be off-putting.  What you're interpreting as reluctance is more wariness, and the expectation that the reality of how gray questions of soundness and completeness are for tools like Infer undermines the viability of these sorts of exercises.  In particular, Infer uses both sound techniques and heuristics which are neither sound nor complete.  Additionally, Infer uses the classical logical notion of soundness, which seems to correspond more to what you term completeness.  Infer does not do any reasoning that fits what you term "soundness".  The other difficulty is that the logically robust reasoning that Infer does produces specifications that are used internally by Infer, but not directly reported to developers.  Evaluating the correctness of these specifications is nontrivial, since they are hypothetical statements with very involved premisses.

@brotherpaul143 I think a good summary is that Infer comes from sound design principles, makes unsound compromises and heuristics where it makes sense. In particular, Infer tries to maximize the value given to developers, over soundness or completeness concerns.

Now that all the provisos are out of the way, the main question is whether, given these provisos, you think that the results will be useful for SATE V. I guess this is for you to assess.

As a side note, I like to split things up in 2 separate aspects: report rate and fix rate.
Report rate measures how many defects that exist, are reported.
Fix rate measures how many reported issues are fixed by developers.

The reason for split things up in this way is that: first, the developer is part of the picture, the source of the value judgement. So the focus is to issue reports that bring value to the developer, as measured by the developer's willingness to act on the reports.
This set-up includes the situation with type checkers, that over-report by definition, but have a perfect fix rate (developers address type errors in order to compile the code).

@cristianoc thanks, I believe I understand now. Infer's approach sounds eminently practical. You're right though: with the heuristics filtering results before they reach the user, Infer is not a candidate for the Ockham criteria track in SATE VI. However, Infer would fit very well in other tracks in SATE VI.

Again, thanks for patiently answering my questions, @jberdine and @jvillard too.

> How do I find out whether a certain line is enclosed within a try block, or is followed by a catch block?

This is going to be a bit cumbersome with our current checkers setup, but it can be done in a hacky way. Let me explain how to do this by modifying the `exec_instr` function in the checker [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/checkers/liveness.ml).

I say `maybe` in the second function because it will also report the end of a catch block early if the catch block contains a loop. But for your use-case of detecting empty catches, this should work just fine.

> How do I find the type of the Exception being caught by the catch?

For each exception type `e` caught by the catch block, there will be an instruction performing an `instanceof` check on `e` to decide whether to enter the catch block or not.

> How do I find whether a certain instruction is part of a catch block, or how do I find what instructions are present in a certain catch block?

I would use the utility functions above to know when you are in a catch block, then create a mapping from catch blocks to the instructions they contain.

This is in reference to #422 . 

Consider that an object of type `T` is null and is being dereferenced, within a `try...catch` that handles `NullPointerException`. Shouldn't this be treated differently from a case in which the `try...catch` doesn't handle the null dereference at all?

From how I see this, probably we can show a warning to the user, saying, `"Maybe you should handle this derefence properly, although the try...catch seems to be handling this."`

Strictly speaking, it's true that the code will not generate an NPE. That said, the choice Infer makes is to report anyway. If a project deliberately catches `NullPointerException`, Infer will produce a lot of unintended reports. For such projects (if they exist), a different message would help.

I suspect that it would be hard to implement that behaviour in infer: if `foo()` dereferences null, then infer will want to report on `foo()`. But maybe `foo()` is only called from inside `bar()`, which catches `Exception` or `NullPointerException`. Currently, infer has no way to know every context in which `foo()` is called prior to analysing `foo()`, so it would be hard to avoid reporting on `foo()`.

That said, as @martinoluca was saying in #422, such code patterns are dubious at best anyway.

Just curious to know:
- Which source files contain the logic for maintaining context and for composition?
It seems that the `type t` represents the Graph, `Procname.t` represents each node in the Graph and `Cfg.re` has functions to modify the graph. Is my understanding correct?

Which `type t` are you talking about? `git grep 'type t\b' infer/src/` returns 223 results ;)

`Procname` is a module for procedure names. A `Cfg` object contains the control-flow graph of all the functions defined in a given file, but by no means of all the procedures in a program. Those are stored on disk in infer-out/captured/.

The logic to analyse functions and in which order lives in ondemand.ml and interproc.ml. Roughly, Infer analyses each function independently. If a function `f()` calls another function `g()`, infer will go and analyse `g()` first (to get its pre- and post-conditions, called "specs", and store them on disk in infer-out/specs/), then go back to analysing `f()`. The only information that is kept around from one function to the other is its set of specs.

I have a getter in a class that returns an Object. When a function of this object is called (eg. `a.getObject().doSomething();`), infer does not trigger a warning for a possible NullPointerException. Is this the designed behaviour or is this an issue at my end? If this is the designed behaviour, is there a good way of ensuring such things don't pass on to production?

Can you provide a full minimal example that reproduces your issue? Shooting from the hip, you could add a `@Nullable` annotation to the return of your getter method so that Infer assumes it can return null.

More (speculative) details: When Infer doesn't know about a function for whatever reason (no implementation available, or Infer failed to analyse it), Infer will treat that function "angelically" and assume that eg it never returns null. This is done to prevent being too noisy. This may or may not be what's happening in your case, we'd need to see some code to know for sure.
Closing for now, please reopen with more info if this is still an issue with the latest version.

I was wondering if it is impossible to change the builtin model of `malloc` such that it always returns a non-null pointer.

malloc can return null. So it would be an incorrect model of the semantics of malloc. 
There are other functions that do not return null for example xmalloc.
@ddino what if user defined a `malloc` function, will Infer always use its built-in model?

Unfortunately, the model for `malloc` is currently baked into the backend, so the only way to change Infer's handling of `malloc` is to change the backend itself. If you change `execute_alloc Sil.Mmalloc true` to `execute_alloc Sil.Mmalloc false` [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/modelBuiltins.ml#L1117), Infer will treat `malloc` as if it never returns null.
There is configuration option being added that will allow to change behavior of malloc (specifically whether it can return null). Stay tuned
I'm adding an option to choose a different behaviour for `malloc`, stay tuned.

3. The length of 'a' doesn't seem to matter, I believe because Infer applies an abstraction for loops and assumes that after a couple of correct loops it will work on loops for arbitrary size, or is this a wrong assumption and does Infer know something about the exact size of array's and lists?

Sorry to be so slow in answering your questions!

(1) I don't fully understand this. The precondition `{ i |-> _ * val |-> _ * this.a |-> j * ls(j,i') * i' |-> _  }` is one that you wrote by hand, not one that Infer produced, right? Infer doesn't introduce inductive `ls` predicates for arrays, so it has no notion of an `i'`.

(2) Yes, Infer knows to add proof obligations for array bounds, and this is indeed what results in the `PRECONDITION_NOT_MET`. Although Infer can report some basic array bounds errors (check out `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsExceptionExample` in the tests), these errors are not reported by default because they tend to bit a bit noisy. You can ask Infer to report them by running with the `-nf` flag.

Even though these errors are off by default, Infer can run into situations where it encounters a `PRECONDITION_NOT_MET`. This means that the caller cannot satisfy the precondition for its callee, but it also doesn't know what the consequences of not satisfying the precondition are--will it result in an out of bounds access, a null dereference, or was the inferred precondition just not general enough?

(3) Infer only knows about the exact size of arrays, and even then only if the size of the array is a constant. In other cases, Infer does indeed apply abstraction in loops to compute pre/postconditions that are independent of the size of an array/list.

Hope this helps, am happy to clarify or answer more questions!

There are two things you can look at:
- The IR consists of [control flow graphs](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/3a2a6c7c448f89fb294e6613b84b0ed72379c816/infer/src/IR/Cfg.re#L68-L75) (one for each source file) of [nodes](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/3a2a6c7c448f89fb294e6613b84b0ed72379c816/infer/src/IR/Cfg.re#L31-L55), described in the [Cfg file](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/3a2a6c7c448f89fb294e6613b84b0ed72379c816/infer/src/IR/Cfg.re). Each node contains instructions, as described in the [Sil.re file](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/3a2a6c7c448f89fb294e6613b84b0ed72379c816/infer/src/IR/Sil.re#L794-L811).
- You can generate .dot files representing the control flow graph of a source file (which will contain all procedures defined in that file) by running infer with the `--debug` option for Java, or the `--frontend-debug` option for the clang frontend (see `infer --help`). This creates one `infer-out/captured/<source file name>.<hash>/icfg.dot` file per source file, containing the cfg of that file. This file is in the [DOT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOT_%28graph_description_language%29) format. You can also run with `--debug` for either Java or clang and look at the generated html file in `infer-out/caputer/<source file name>.<hash>.html` and if you hover over `I` nodes (or click on them) you'll see the IR instructions executed at that program point.

Have you taken a look at the debug [HTML](http://fbinfer.com/docs/advanced-features.html) that is produced when running using the `--debug` option? This gives a very readable representation of the IR, especially because you see the IR next to the source code that produced it.

I was wondering:
- is there any documentation that explains how to extend Infer to other programming languages or to add rules to "infer more"?
- is Flow the Infer implementation for Javascript ?

Flow and Infer are two unrelated projects. 

There is no generic documentation describing precisely how to extend Infer to a new languages. Basically, what needs to be done is to trans-compile the input source code into the Infer intermediate representation. The [Infer IR](https://github.com/facebook/infer/tree/master/infer/src/IR) is a low level description of types, expressions, instructions and control flow. The code of the intermediate representation is written in [Reason](https://facebook.github.io/reason/) which has a syntax close to Javascript. Reading the documentations of the `.rei` files, example: [Sil.rei](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/IR/Sil.rei) is a good way to understand how to write a new frontend.

There is currently one frontend for [Java](https://github.com/facebook/infer/tree/master/infer/src/java) and one for [Clang](https://github.com/facebook/infer/tree/master/infer/src/clang). They can be used ass input examples.

Just for curiosity, what kind of issues are you interested to detect with Infer in Javascript code ?

The taint analysis is an experimental feature that's still under development, but I can share a few details on what it can do now.
- The taint checks Infer does fall into two categories: security and privacy. Security checks ensure that user-controlled input does not flow to sensitive functions, and privacy checks ensure that sensitive user data does not escape to the outside.
- There are a few built in taint checks in the open-source version of Infer (most notably, the SSL hostname verification check), but you can also specify your own sources and sinks using the [`PrivacySource`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/annotations/com/facebook/infer/annotation/PrivacySource.java), `PrivacySink`, `IntegritySource`, and `IntegritySink` annotations. Once you add these annotations, Infer will report source-sink flows between the annotations.
- At the theoretical level, the taint analysis works using the same bi-abduction technique that Infer uses to compute function pre and postconditions. When the analysis encounters a taint sink, it generates a proof obligation that flows into that sink are untainted, and it propagates that proof obligation into the precondition. When applying that precondition at a call site where the precondition cannot be met, Infer will report a warning.

The functionality for propagating tainted sources to tainted sinks lives in the main bi-abduction analysis, so you won't be able to leverage it from a custom checker.

I don't fully understand what you are trying to do with your checker, but if you explain a bit more I can try to help.

I would like to implement a checker such that it is able to detect programs that attempt to download files over the internet and perform operations (e.g. unzipping or executing) with the files that have been downloaded. 

Hence the thoughts of utilizing and tracking tainted variables would be very useful to detect such patterns.

If you want to implement such a checker from scratch, Infer's abstract interpretation framework for checkers would be quite suitable for this. See `liveness.ml` for an example of a simple AbsInt checker and `annotationReachability.ml` for an example of a more advanced one.

However, if you want to take advantage of Infer's builtin capabilities for propagating taint, you'll have to build your checker on top of the core bi-abduction algorithm. This would probably be simpler; you should just need to add the methods you care about as sources and sinks. See `inferTaint.ml` for examples of how to to this.

Hello @jeremydubreil, very nice to receive your message.
You are right that Infer dose not know `docvrid` is null. Actually `docvrid` is not always null, it's potentially null. So, `docvrid != null && !docvrid.equals("10000103")` will be safe and `docvrid.equals("10000103")` without `docvrid != null` is dangerous.

In my opinion the dangerous code should be print. Can Infer print the potentially NullPointerException?

In theory, Infer could report every time there is not enough information to prove that a variable being dereference is not null. But in practice, this will generate way too many reports and could make the tool unusable.

If you want more demonic behavior w.r.t nullability, you might want to give eradicate a try (`infer -a eradicate -- <your_compile_command>`). Eradicate requires more annotations than Infer, but is also more exhaustive in reporting NPE warnings.
Check out my answer to https://github.com/facebook/infer/issues/383 to see another way to make Infer's NPE reporting more aggressive.

Thanks for the detailed question, @wouter89. What you are seeing is because infer doesn't do a global analysis of a class (in this case `NoNullDereference`) to figure out invariants (in this case "`alwaysFalse` is always `false`"). To explain, let me try and go over your tests:
1. Infer analyses `test()` on its own (without looking at the context) and finds that it could dereference `null` if `alwaysFalse` is `true`. Since infer doesn't try to analyse the context of the method, only the method itself, it doesn't know that `alwaysFalse` cannot in fact be `true`. The analysis of `main()` shows no error.
2. Same as 1, except this time it turns out that `alwaysTrue` can indeed be `true` to this report turns out to be legit.
3. Infer analyses `test()` and finds no issue. It stores 2 specifications about `test()`: A) when `alwaysTrue` is `true` then the return value is `null`; B) otherwise it is `"hello"`. Infer then analyses `main()`. At the point where `main()` calls `test()`, the value of `nullDereference.alwaysTrue` is `true`, so infer uses specification A and then finds an error when simulating the execution of `null.trim()`.
4. Similar to 3, except than at the point where `main()` calls `test()` infer selects specification B and doesn't find any error when symbolically executing `"hello".trim()`.
5. Infer analyses `test()` and finds no error because it knows which branch to take in `if (false) ...`.
6. Same as 5 and Infer correctly finds the NPE.

I hope this answers your question. Feel free to open another issue about the general fact that infer doesn't try to find out which fields never change before anaylising the methods in a class.

It's possible that the compiler is optimizing out large parts of the code simply because it appears unreachable in some way.

David

Hi David,
  Infer should analyze every file that is compiled regardless of whether functions in that file are called from elsewhere. How are you building the project?

I'm currently just building if from the top level file, main.c, using clang:
infer -- clang -c main.c -I api -I app_sim -I app

Infer will only analyze source files passed to clang during the process of executing the build command.  So for:

> infer -- clang -c main.c -I api -I app_sim -I app

only the functions defined in main.c will be analyzed.  Are the null dereference errors you mentioned in main.c, or elsewhere?
They are in one of the sub files, tried running infer by pointing it to the subfile, but I didn't get my expected error (to be fair, almost no other tool shows the error).

You can test that the function is being analyzed by inserting a bug infer should report, such as `int* p = NULL; *p = 42;`, and checking that this is indeed reported.

I'm thinking that perhaps the issue is a little too difficult to find, it was originally pointed out to me by someone running klocwork.  It looks like great tool, it just might not be what we need.

if(some_pointer != nil){//some code here}

Hi Forrest,
  Our motivation for this check is to avoid confusion between a `nil` pointer and a pointer to the numerical value value zero. In our experience, the type coercions in Objective-C make it easy to accidentally write `if (some_pointer)` when you actually meant `if ([some_pointer intValue])`.

I am a little bit confused by what you are trying to do. A static method cannot override an instance method. So although `getItemId` could be static, you can't both make it static and override the method of the superclass. Doing so will give you a compiler error, at least for Java <= 7. Ah, I understand. You are trying to avoid warning on this method for exactly this reason :).

I think that you will probably need to write custom logic for this (but please do send a pull request, as this logic could be useful elsewhere!). 

Given a method `m`, I would look up its struct type `T` using `Tenv.proc_extract_declaring_class_typ`. Each `struct_typ` knows what its immediate superclasses and declared methods are. I would iterate through the declared methods of each supertype of `T` looking for methods `m_super` whose name is the same as `m` (for full precision, you'll have to check the the correct subtyping relationship holds on the parameters of `m` and `m_super` as well). This should be done recursively for all superclasses of `T` until you find a match. The code from `AndroidFramework.get_all_supertypes` might be useful to reuse/adapt for this.

To print instructions and expressions, you can use `Sil.d_exp` and `Sil.d_instr`. What these do is print to the debug buffer associated with each node in the HTML debug output. You can print strings to this same buffer using `Logging.d_strln`.

You can also use `Logging.stdout`/`Logging.stderr` with the pretty-printers for expressions and instrs `Sil.pp_exp`, `Sil.pp_instr`.

These pretty-printers require a `printenv`, and the one you want is almost always `pe_text`. So, an example might look like:

`Logging.stderr "This expression is %a@." (Sil.pp_exp pe_text) exp`.

Is there a way to modify infer to support analysing the JVM bytecode instead of java code?

No immediate plan yet, but in principle there's nothing stopping Infer from starting from the bytecode, as all the heavy-lifting is done at this level already. In particular, Infer starts from the JVM bytecode to analyse Java files. Some work is needed to get rid of the dependency on the source code itself.

What part of the source code is responsible for that?
I mean the dependency on java source files.
I'd like to start playing with it, and maybe submit a patch

On 2016 март 21, дүш 17:50 Jules Villard notifications@github.com wrote:

> No immediate plan yet, but in principle there's nothing stopping Infer
> from starting from the bytecode, as all the heavy-lifting is done at this
> level already. In particular, Infer starts from the JVM bytecode to analyse
> Java files. Some work is needed to get rid of the dependency on the source
> code itself.
> 
> —
> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.
> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub
> https://github.com/facebook/infer/issues/308#issuecomment-199323275

This would be great to have!

At a high level, what our Java frontend currently does is (for each invocation of `javac`, directly or by the build system):
(1) Start from the verbose output of `javac`, which lists the classpath, list of compiled source files, and produced bytecodes)
(2) Build a map from produced bytecodes to their source files
(3) Use Javalib (a third-party-library) to parse the produced bytecode
(4) Translate all of the Javalib-parsed bytecodes into SIL (Infer's intermediate language)

To support other JVM languages, it probably makes the most sense to add code for passing a JAR directly to step (3). Unfortunately, the logic for steps for (1) - (3) is not cleanly separated. It will likely require some refactoring before you can add the JAR option.

I would start from [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/java/jClasspath.ml#L161), which is what does steps (2) and (3). The first step would be separating out (3) so you can pass it a JAR directly. Then, we can work on the trickier problem of replicating (2): how do you get reliable source line/variable name information starting from bytecode :).

Let me know if you have any questions!

@hzsweers apologies for the code... that group is used to define annotations that have the property `ia_is_inject`, which suppresses `FIELD_NOT_NULLABLE`.

Ah interesting, should `ia_is_inject_view` be updated to include `bind` as well or is that left out since Butter Knife 7+ started using `Nullable` instead of `Optional`?
@hzsweers I don't know the internal details of Butter Knife. If using it leads to `FIELD_NOT_NULLABLE` reports then we should include `bind` into `ia_is_inject_view` (or the better name for it).

Basically:

**Butter Knife 6** and before: `@InjectView` would cause a runtime exception if the view was null after binding. Could optionally add `@Optional` if you wanted to allow for nulls. Behavior applies to fields and methods.

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

**Butter Knife 7**: `@Bind` was the same as `@InjectView` functionally, but `@Optional` was removed in favor of reusing `@Nullable` so the IDE would lint it. Same idea though. Behavior applies to fields and methods.

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

**Butter Knife 8+**: Unreleased, but behavior will be the same with fields. For methods however, `@Optional` was re-added because it was strange to require `@Nullable` for methods since many had `void` return types. Note that it's only allowed on methods however, fields must still use `@Nullable`

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

---

All in all: I think `bind` should be included as well then since its behavior is functionally the same and this only applies to fields. The problem arises in the situation where you have both `@Nullable` and `@Bind` annotations on a field, which I'm not sure if infer is aware and can ensure that `@Nullable` overrules.

The parameter `proc_name` is the name of the function/method. Every checker, when active, is called once for each function.

What will my `ret_id1..ret_idn, e_fun, arg_ts, loc, call_flags` look like?

- `ret1...retn` is the empty list, as this is a void function.
- `e_fun` is a constant to denote this specific function: `void PrintStream.println(String)`. The constant function is a `Cfun`.
- `args_ts` are the arguments of the function call: `n$0` and `n$1` with their respective types. These are variables of the intermediate language: their scope ends at `REMOVE_TEMPS`. In this case, `n$0` is `this`: in the intermediate language `this` is an explicit argument.
- `loc` is the location: the current file at line 13.
- `call_flags` specifies that the function is virtual. This will be true for any non-static java method.

- one day: infer analyses and reports bugs on java 8 code

- Run `javac` over your source files to produce Java 8 bytecode.
- Retrolambda transforms the bytecode to be Java 6/7 compatible.
- `dx` transforms the transformed bytecode into a `.dex` file.

Thanks for the detailed update @crm416. Skipping Java 8 files and not crashing is the expected behaviour, there's a fix in 0.8.0 to reintroduce it.

For infer to be able to analyse code compiled with retrolambda, one of these two things needs to happen:
1. Java 8 support is added to Infer (#314)
2. Support for starting from the bytecode instead of from the Java source is added to Infer (#308)

1 is planned, and there's nothing stopping 2 in principle, since our Java frontend already starts from Java bytecode (only some rearchitecturing is needed to be able to not start from the sources).

I'm closing this issue since it's been resolved. Use the other two issues to track progress on the larger issue of dealing with Java8 bytecode.

Thanks for the report @btakeya, I managed to reproduce the issue locally, we'll look into it.
this issue happens when running via docker (Infer version: v0.7.0)

This error comes from [`DB.source_file_equal (Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname) source_file`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L526).

The exact bug point is the function [`DB.rel_source_file_from_abs_path`]().
When the function with "/" parameter `DB.rel_source_file_from_abs_path "/" "/root/a.c"`, then it returns `Relative "/root/a.c"`.

I will explain how this bug make Infer skip analyzing procedures when run Infer on "/".

When I run Infer on `/` directory, then the `source_file` type is '[Absolute](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/DB.ml#L19)'. However, `(Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)` returns '[Relative](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/DB.ml#L20)' type value, because of [DB. rel_source_file_from_abs_path](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/DB.ml#L53) returns 'Relative' type value.
Thus, it causes '0 active procedures' in [created clusters](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L532), and analyzer does not analyze procedures in a source file.
I will explain how code set `source_file` as 'Absolute' type value, and set `(Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)` as 'Relative' type value.

At first, the result of `DB.source_file_to_string source_file` and `DB.source_file_to_string (Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)` is same string, as absolute path form string, when I run Infer on / directory
So I checked the reason of returning false, and the type of `source_file` is 'Absolute', and the type of `(Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)` is 'Relative'.
It is natural that the type of  `source_file` is 'Absolute', because of the variable comes from [`this line`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L512), (the `source_file` is set by a function [`ClusterMakefile.source_file_from_pname`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L512) and the function calls the function [`DB.source_file_from_string`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/DB.ml#L42)).

However, type of the result of `(Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)` is 'Relative', so I followed code to find an origin of the `(Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname)`.
The value `exe_env` is set from [this statements](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L908-L909), and more specifically, [this statement](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/inferanalyze.ml#L748).
I traced more code to find specific values in exe_env, and I found [`load_from_file` function](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/exe_env.ml#L87) which loads cg values from serialized file.

Thus I try to find call sites of the function [`store_to_file` which is pair with `load_from_file`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/cg.ml#L325-L343), and the call sites are following,
- [in clang/cFrontend.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/clang/cFrontend.ml#L163).
- [in java/jMain.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/java/jMain.ml#L105).
- [in llvm/lMain.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/llvm/lMain.ml#L55).
- [in harness/inhabit.ml](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/harness/inhabit.ml#L292).

As a result of this long code trip, I finally found [a line which causes this bug, in function `DB.rel_source_file_from_abs_path`](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/DB.ml#L54) which is called in the above `store_to_file` call sites.
The call sites of `store_to_file` call the vulnerable function `DB.rel_source_file_from_abs_path` to prepare `cg`.
The prepared `cg` is stored using `Cg.store_to_file` function, and it is loaded by `Cg.load_from_file` function, and it makes `DB.source_file_equal (Exe_env.get_source exe_env pname) source_file` statement returns false, which is cause of this bug.

Also I checked that same problem when run `infer -- java /path-to-code/Hello.c` on `/`, but other cases (llvm/lMain.ml, harness/inhabit.ml (?)) are not confirmed whether the function `DB.rel_source_file_from_abs_path` is called to prepare `cg (or callgraph)`.

The reason is that new fedora has new version of ABI and we were trying to link clang built with old ABI and plugin built with new ABI.

The existing fields in the json are expected to be stable, but extra fields may be added in the future (eg e11395d1998cacfa2309a27e7bd6cd6fd30d8bc9 adds a new optional `infer_source_loc` field).
- `bug_class` is for development purposes.
- `kind` is either `"ERROR"`, `"WARNING"`, or `"INFO"`: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/lib/python/inferlib/issues.py#L30-L32
- `bug_type` is one of the errors listed here: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/localise.ml#L31-L68, although a lot of these are not reported by default. The ones not filtered out are listed in the python toplevel: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/lib/python/inferlib/issues.py#L35-L50
- `qualifier` is a free-form string describing the bug, eg, `"pointer s last assigned on line 13 could be null and is dereferenced at line 14, column 3"`.
- `severity` is one of these: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/errlog.ml#L139-L141
Thanks!

  Thanks for this report and your others. Unfortunately, you have run into one of the dark corners of Infer: our Java 8 support. The frontend we use to parse Java bytecodes is a third-party library that does not yet support Java 8 (we are working on encouraging the maintainers to add support or do it ourselves). As a result, some classes may parse incorrectly, and some may fail to parse altogether. I will look into this issue and see if it is something unrelated to Java 8, but just a heads-up that anything using Java 8 can lead to strange results.

I looked into this. What is happening is not related to Java 8. Instead, the analysis times out on the constructor for `AttributeMetadata`, which means that it does not know the fields have been initialized to a non-null value. We will work on fixing the timeout and/or making the analysis act more angelically in such cases.

Thanks for reporting this; definitely not the intended behavior for Infer.

The shallow reason that Infer gets this example wrong is that we don't have a model for MockCursor. This issue can be fixed by adding a model for `MockCursor` (see the SqlLiteCursor [model](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/models/java/src/android/database/sqlite/SQLiteCursor.java) for an example of how to do this).

The deeper reason is that Infer has problems identifying what concrete method an interface method call like `Cursor.close` will invoke. We are working on fixing this.
Thanks for the quick response. Good to know you're on this.

Just a request to update the title to include `MockCursor` or the interface -> concrete method calls info – I found this because I was thinking infer did not dive into method calls but it seems this is specific interface -> concrete methods & the `MockCursor`.

A Cursor object given to a CursorAdapter cannot be closed immediately because the CursorAdapter will use this Cursor object later on.

The open Cursor can only be closed after the CursorAdapter has created its views.

One way to close the open Cursor is to call [changeCursor(null)](http://developer.android.com/reference/android/widget/CursorAdapter.html#changeCursor%28android.database.Cursor%29) what will make the adapter close the last Cursor.

For example, the following test case:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

Results in:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

The problem here is that Infer doesn't handle the Android lifecycle, so it doesn't know that `onDestroy` will always be called after `onCreate` and close the `Cursor`. 

However, even if it did understand the lifecycle, it would still complain about this example. The reason is that if an uncaught exception is thrown in `super.onDestroy()`, `testCursorAdapter.changeCursor(null)` will never be called and the `Cursor` will remain open.
Good point! You're right. `testCursorAdapter.changeCursor(null)` should be called before `super.onDestroy()`. Thanks for the note. I'll change this in the original project I took this sample from.
Looks like the report was legit after all. Feel free to open a more general issue about infer not knowing about the android lifecycle.

Hello @tianyutingxy,
can you please provide more information about how you are getting this problem?

Thanks.

Thanks @tianyutingxy for reporting this. It seems to me that the Gradle integration is creating javac command lines with a number of file exceeding the bash limit. The current Gradle integration is mostly a proof of concept to show that we can analyze Gradle projects with Infer but is very fragile. We are working on a much more robust way to integrate Infer with Java built systems. I will update this issue once it is ready.

The gradle integration reads the list of Java files to compile from a file, not from the command line, precisely to avoid this error (#131) . Without more information, it's hard to know what's wrong here, so I'm closing this task. Feel free to re-open with more info.

A common mistake is to write `if(value)` when intending to test whether `value` is a non-zero integer, while the code actually tests whether `value` is `nil`.  If you instead write `if(value != nil)` explicitly, then the warning should not be reported.
Thank you @jberdine
Some documentation: http://fbinfer.com/docs/infer-bug-types.html#BAD_POINTER_COMPARISON

Turning to wishlist.

Thank you for your reply, and good to know this is on the wishlist. As a workaround, I tried to add a model of the method with the correct throws clause. However, it seems that adding a model that throws exceptions doesn't help in this case.  Is this also not supported yet?

Eradicate uses a different modeling mechanism than the core Infer analysis, with tables for annotations instead of actual code, as the implementation of called methods is not used by Eradicate's analysis.
It would be easy to add tables for exceptions as well, as a temporary solution while the full solution is being developed.

Unfortunately, it does not work right now to model the interfaces in order to model all the implementations at once. This is due to an incomplete support for dynamic dispatch in the analyzer. For example, if a method is of the form:

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

Then the model provided for `List.length()` will not be used in the call to `foo(l)` in `bar`.

Hi Infer team,

I have recently used Infer to analyse a few opensource iOS projects for a university subject. I came across 3 retain cycles detected by Infer from the same application and file.

These are the 3 bugs reported:
aMenjar-master/aMenjar/AMQRPedidoViewController.m:638: error: RETAIN_CYCLE
  Retain cycle involving the following objects:  (1) an object of class MBProgressHUD  retaining another object via instance variable _delegate,  (2) object self retaining self._HUD,   at line 638, column 5

aMenjar-master/aMenjar/AMQRPedidoViewController.m:765: error: RETAIN_CYCLE
  Retain cycle involving the following objects:  (1) object self retaining self._btnDer,  (2) an object of class UIBarButtonItem  retaining another object via instance variable _target,   at line 765, column 5

aMenjar-master/aMenjar/AMResumenIpadViewController.m:611: error: RETAIN_CYCLE
  Retain cycle involving the following objects:  (1) an object of class MBProgressHUD  retaining another object via instance variable _delegate,  (2) object self retaining self._HUD,   at line 611, column 5

The application is called aMenjar and its Github location can be found at https://github.com/maurovc/aMenjar.

The 1st bug is between the class AMQRPedidoViewController (self) that has a property of type MBProgressHUD (a strong pointer), MBProgressHUD has a property delegate that is set to AMQRPedidoViewController at line 638 stated. The pointer to the delegate is a weak pointer. So according to the documentation, if 2 objects are pointing to each other, and one of them is strong pointer and the other is a weak pointer, then a retain cycle does not exist as eventually, one of the object can be released and thus the other will be released.

The 3rd bug is the same as the 1st bug

The 2nd bug is for the class AMQRPedidoViewController having a property named btnDer of type UIBarButtonItem. This is a weak pointer from the self object to btnDer. In UIBarButtonItem, there is a target property that can be set. In line 744, [self.btnDer setTarget:self]; is called, hence setting AMQRPedidoViewController as the target of btnDer. Though the target property in UIBarButtonItem is a weak pointer. So the retain cycle does not establish between 2 weak pointers as no ownership is present for both objects.

I think that the bugs reported maybe false alarm, but let me know otherwise if I was incorrect.

Many thanks for your help.

hi, 
you are right these are false positives. 

Thanks for reporting them. We will work to improve infer reporting on retain cycles.

I suspect what's happening in your case is that the makefiles are running the compiler providing an absolute path rather than a relative one. In this case Infer won't be able to capture the compile commands (because it does it by changing the PATH environment variable, which won't be effective in this case).

Usually you can replace the compilers on Makefiles setting variables like CC and CXX: try setting those to point to your compiler, but without specifying the absolute path. If there's a `configure` step that generates these makefiles, then run it again setting those variables first.

Hi @b0207191,

You probably don't need to use dest-$CC to compile infer and the facebook-clang-plugins. (The error you get is because your dest-$CC is indeed too old)

The Makefile you pasted does not seem to contain any build rules, it just calls other Makefiles. To be able to help, it would be great to see an example invocation of the compiler as called by your Makefiles.

One possibility for your issue is if your Makefile gives several source files to $CC at once. Infer cannot deal with this. For instance, `infer -- gcc -c a.c b.c` does not work. Instead, one should use `infer -- gcc -c a.c && infer -- gcc -c b.c`. I realise now that we seem to have forgotten to document this!

You need a specific version of facebook-clang-plugins to compile infer. Usually the latest version of the plugin does not work with infer. You can find which version of the facebook-clang-plugins you need in [dependencies/clang-plugin/clang-plugin-version.config](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/dependencies/clang-plugin/clang-plugin-version.config).

For instance, to compile the current infer master, you need https://github.com/facebook/facebook-clang-plugins/archive/3a4b470518da7251f2dc296444c4d616fef5dc2c.zip.

The easiest way to get the right version of the plugin is to simply remove your current facebook-clang-plugins/ directory and run `./update-fcp.sh` from inside infer, which will get the right version for you.
