Is it possible for models to understand annotations? For example, I would like to have assertions on the parameters of a method with a particular example. I had a look at the models defined as part of infer and none of them use annotations.

If this is not currently possible, how difficult would it be to implement this? Can anyone point me to where I can get started?
Hi @vikhyat. It is in theory possible to use annotations with Infer but so far we did not need it. Do you have a concrete example in mind where using annotations in the models would be good ?

One example would be Spring's @Autowired annotation, fields with that annotation should be treated as constructor-initialized but currently the Eradicate checker complains that they need to be marked as @Nullable since they are not initialized in the constructor.

The actual use-case for which I posted this question is that I have some methods with @Validated annotations, for which there are a number of constraints I want to apply to the arguments.

Adding support for @Autowired is going to be easy: we already support @Inject with the same effect of not requiring fields to be initialized, so it's just a matter of recognizing one more annotation.

For @Validated, it's hard to say without knowing what are the constraints and what effect they should have.

My use-case is mostly not null constraints on a bean that is passed to the method that are not enforced globally, it is quite similar to [Hibernate Validator](http://hibernate.org/validator/). The annotation is similar to [how it is done in Dropwizard](https://dropwizard.github.io/dropwizard/manual/core.html#validation) except that it is applied to the method rather than the argument.

One option I have could be to exclude the beans from Infer and provide an auto-generated model in it's place, but the problem with that is that it will be used for all occurrences of the bean rather than just the places where it is validated.

Summary:
Infer currently exits with exit code 0 whether the analysis returns
errors or not.  Return exit code 1 instead when there are errors, so
i.e. a CI server can interpret the results without parsing the output.

Test plan:
Run infer on a project with and without errors.

Hi @tgummerer, thanks for your diff! We're still in discussion about what to do and others have requested this feature as well (eg, #139).

We'll likely want to gate this behaviour behind a command-line option to Infer. Moreover, it would be good to implement this for other modules than just buck so that Infer behaves consistently on different build systems.

There are cases where we do not want to exit with 1 when infer finds an error. A typical example is to add infer on the CI of an existing project. Then it will fail all the time until all the existing bugs are fixed which may take time.

A possible approach is to run Infer on the CI as it is, keeping the exit code 0 for a successful analysis, and create the exist code as a separate step:

  infer -o out  -- buck build target
  check_errors -o out/report.json

Adding a command line option is a possible approach but there are many different way in which Infer can be used on CI.
Example of creating failures as an extra step: https://github.com/thyrlian/jooi

@jvillard thanks for having a look!  Maybe it could be hidden behind a `--exit-code` flag.  I don't use infer with any of the other modules currently, but if there is interest in including this I could try to add to them as well.

@jeremydubreil That makes sense, I didn't think about that use case.  Thanks for the example. Personally I would prefer to avoid an extra script on the CI server though.

@tgummerer in the end I implemented something slightly more general that works for any infer module, not just buck: e63269fa14f360249612407d13cd47e35566ec48

hi GeemMin,

Your question is interesting and it does not have a definite answer. But let me give you a bit of context.

Static analysis is an undecidable problem, therefore there are no algorithmic methods that can solve it perfectly for every instance. For this theoretical reason, all static analysis tools are obliged to use some heuristic algorithms trying to find an approximate solution to the problem.  Heuristics are imprecise 
therefore all existing static analyzers are imprecise. They work well in some programs and less well in others. 
That said, every static analyzer has its own heuristic and internal engine and therefore they will always
be differences in their results. One will find something and another wiill find something else. 
Sometimes two different analyzers find the same bug. But there is no general rule that can tell you 
who can find what. In general we can only make predictions. 
So even if on the surface two different analyzers say that they find the same category of bugs 
(for example null pointer dereference) in reality, their heuristic normally would fire in different situations.
For this  reason many large companies employing static analysis use more than one  analyzer on the same code to discover the same category of bugs.

A good article comparing different existing analyzers is the following:
http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/TD/td3202/32_02-Pendergrass-Lee.pdf

I hope this helps!

Retain cycle involving the following objects:  (1) an object of class TYPE_A  retaining another object via instance variable _varForWeakPropertyInA,  (2) an object of class TYPE_B  retaining another object via instance variable _varForStrongPropertyinB,  (3) an object of class TYPE_C  retaining another object via instance variable _varForWeakPropertyInC,   

So, in this cycle, two of the instance variables are for weak properties.  One thing that might be causing the problem is that the properties are declared this way in the `@interface` in the .h

When analysing some simple linked list C code I found that infer would either fail to generate any specs for some functions, or would only provide specs for short, fixed-length lists.  After some debugging, I found that the backend sometimes fails to detect recursive fields in `struct`s because the type comparison relies on the fields in the struct type having the same order.  The clang frontend produces `struct` types with the fields in the declared order, but parts of the backend sort them and `sil.mli` says they should always be sorted.

For example, in the following code

<S_CODE_TOKEN>

I get specs for `add1` where the fields are in alphabetical order, but not for `add2`.

Hi Brian, 
thanks so much for reporting this issue. Yes, it seems that the frontend is not sorting the fields and it should. I'll work on it.

Just to be clear: The core infer team does not have a use case for windows support, and does not have time to allocate to this.  If someone wants to work on this, I expect that there is a bit of work to do to generalize the build scripts to work on (even one of the ~6 OCaml ports for) windows.  Building the dependencies will likely involve some work.  After that, some of the build system integration implementations rely on a posix environment, but the degree of dependence varies (e.g. high for 'make', low for 'buck').  So depending on which build system you need, there is some work there.  Finally, the core of infer itself has very little reliance on posix, and in various points (e.g. interaction with signals) basic windows support is there (though untested).  If your use case allows using WSL or cygwin, then there might be very little work needed at all.  Pull requests most welcome.

It works fine when I symlink /usr/bin/python to python2.

A solution for linux would be to replace every `#!/usr/bin/env python` line with `#!/usr/bin/env python2`

The problem with changing `#!/usr/bin/env python` to `#!/usr/bin/env python2` is OS X doesn't support [PEP-0394](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0394/) and you'll end up with `python2 not found`.

A better solution would be to support both Python 2.X and Python 3.X. Projects such as [six](https://pythonhosted.org/six/) are design to help with this.

I see from your command line that you are running Infer using the `--debug` option.
`--debug` is telling Infer to emit extra internal information during the analysis and this will make it slower than usual.
If you're interested on the internals of Infer and you want to look at the translation information generated during the analysis, then there's nothing wrong with your analysis instance, you should just wait for the analysis to finish (it may take some time, depending on the size of your codebase).

In case you're just interested in what bugs Infer finds on your code, then you should just remove the `--debug` option and let the analysis run.

Make sure you `./gradlew clean` before running it again, to make sure Infer captures all the compilation commands.

The install scripts are messy, and this causes problems.

`update-fcp.sh` downloads a separate repository (facebook-clang-plugin) into the parent directory of the infer repository.  Running the setup file in this directory can fail, because facebook-clang-plugin contains a gzipped archive of an autoconf'd `llvm`, which can't account for spaces in the prefix dir path (the `facebook-clang-plugin` repository directory, in this case).  This appears to be an autotools problem.

Rather than update the gzipped archive in the facebook-clang-plugin repository, it seems reasonable to control where that dependency is auto-downloaded to.

Workaround
--- 

### Generate a json compilation database
If you add the [following parameter](http://oclint-docs.readthedocs.io/en/stable/guide/xctool.html#running-xctool-with-json-compilation-database-reporter) to 
* `xctool`: `-reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` 
* `xcpretty`:  `-r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json`

#### This'll enable you to use one of the following commands: 
Depending on how you generate this file you use one of the following options:
*  `xcpretty` and `xctool`: `--clang-compilation-db-files-escaped` 
    * reason: the files in the json are escaped : 'file\\ with\\ spaces'
* `cmake`: `--clang-compilation-db-files`

Granted, it'd be a 2 step process, but it'll work 👍 

**NB** Commonly, the build output will be stored in a file called 'xcodebuild.log'. If you need a different reporter for e.g. your test, you can still do that, generate the `compile_commands.json` using that log file, and launch infer using that generated `compile_commands.json`

Concretely:
1. `xctool.sh --<whatever parameters you need> -reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` or `xcodebuild --<whatever parameters> | tee xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r junit -o junit.xml` as usual
2. `cat xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json &> /dev/null`
    * the last part pipes the output  to `/dev/null`, as otherwise it'd be displayed on screen again, convoluting your build log.
3. `infer --skip-analysis-in-path Pods --clang-compilation-db-files-escaped compile_commands.json`

The cleanup attribute does not seem to be supported. I get many many false positives for resource and mem leaks due to this.

> cleanup (cleanup_function)
> The cleanup attribute runs a function when the variable goes out of scope. This attribute can only be applied to auto function scope variables; it may not be applied to parameters or variables with static storage duration. The function must take one parameter, a pointer to a type compatible with the variable. The return value of the function (if any) is ignored.
> 
> If -fexceptions is enabled, then cleanup_function is run during the stack unwinding that happens during the processing of the exception. Note that the cleanup attribute does not allow the exception to be caught, only to perform an action. It is undefined what happens if cleanup_function does not return normally.
> https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Common-Variable-Attributes.html
